segments.text: This is Terry Hanger, and I'm interviewing WC Daniel Jr. from the Daniel Funeral Home here in Bryan, Texas.
Born in the Boonville area.
This day is known as Route 3, Bryant.
That was in February of 1927.
I don't know anything about the Boonville area because when I found myself, I was in Bryant at 409 West 19th Street.
That's all I remember, of course, with Francis Boonville in front.
Since that time both my parents have died, I've gotten good school, and I got married.
And that's just about the gist of my whole life.
Now, there are a few folks here from Danville.
There's, uh, I can remember Jack Cannon, that dude was a man of years.
But most of the old things have passed on now that I still remember.
Well, do you know where your family came from before they were at Booneville?
My father?
Yes.
I don't.
I think I know his parents were in Alabama.
My mother was from Hearns, throughout the county.
She taught school.
He was a minister and a mortician.
Good Lord, did he get the salary that he needed to stay away from the morticians.
I graduated from Southern University in 1947.
I did further study at Texas Southern University in Houston.
I graduated from the Pomeroy College of Motor Science in 1948.
I took the board in 48.
I took my apprenticeship under my father at the old Anglican Home at 700 North Sterling.
Of course, after he passed, I built my own theater.
I married Mrs. She was a lioness.
She was a Miss Lioness Hospital at that time.
That's from the first town in the Wilcox community.
She's got a presence of teaching the blind public schools.
Well, can you tell me, do you know anything about, like, the farming?
When you were in Boonesville, was there farming around in that area?
Yeah, Boonesville was another first farm around.
Can you tell me, like, any new things that you have seen in your lifetime, you know, that have progressed the way the old farming practices were?
Oh, yes, I see.
You know, we've gotten the way everything is mechanized now.
Of course, most of the folk that were there during my time,
They don't.
I mean, they moved.
Those that left, they moved away.
None of the children are there anymore.
They moved away.
Well, now you know how the children are.
They grew up.
They want something.
They got to have a bright life.
Some noise, anyway.
There's nothing else.
So now they're going to be the rural areas.
Because I think I understand there's a trend back to it.
How have I got to see it?
When you first moved to Bryan, it wasn't this developed.
Oh no, Bryan was nothing like it is today.
Bryan wasn't even a city at that time.
Can you just tell me, you know, a few little things that you remember the way it was?
Well...
I heard something that there used to be a lot of saloons on.
ministry or something?
Well, I don't know.
They've had no mouth in here.
Oh, really?
Now, they get more progress than anything, but we have grown to manage this thing from a one-horse town to a two-horse town now.
I promise I'm safe.
Well, what do you think is causing it?
Do you think it was the university or it's just the railroad or the airport?
No, I have to attribute it to the university because the railroad didn't do that much of anything.
I have to attribute all the progress to the university.
I don't know if it would have been for the university.
At that time, you could... Let's get my phone in the sun.
Hello.
Yes, I have a copy from the college.
My brother's here.
Oh, well, you're talking about college now?
You attribute most of the development to college?
As a result of college being bad.
Well, I heard something that there used to be like a trolley car or something that went from Brian to...
Yes, there was.
I don't remember, but I'm saying there was a trolley car system here.
I do know one thing.
That was...
watering trough for cattle in the middle of Main Street.
You might remember that.
Everybody wanted to get it moved.
It never did move.
My mother ran over it.
It was your mother then, huh?
She never tried to
I don't know what that was.
Most likely it was a scar.
My dad used to leave him that scar.
I don't remember whether it was that or not.
But most likely he would have had a scar because that's what he used to have all the time.
I don't remember whether it was that or not.
What about, do you know of any like
influential families that have helped out with growing and development?
Yes.
It's kind of like the history now.
The history books when we were in college and things like Lincoln and Washington, they forget about George Washington.
Here we had, there was a doctor here named
Dr. Mason, Dr. Allen, but even before that, there was another very good doctor, Thompson, Dr. A. E. Thompson.
He was a great asset to this town.
Looks like he's passed on now.
I'm going to tell you how many years he's passed on now.
But when you say flu, H-R-B, flu, ain't it hard to put it?
When you say flu, H-R-B.
your interpretation of the information that we left in from mine, see, well, you would see Mick Dansby.
I would perhaps see Dave C. Dansby.
Mm-hmm.
That's fine.
That's what my mind's like, yeah.

What the people that you think that really stand out in your mind that you can remember that meant something to you and you can see, you know, you've known that they've done something to help out this town.
Or the people that...
I think it was Mr. Thomas.
He was a great asset to this town.
He is past that now.
One of the first gym establishments we had was the Scott Place, which my daddy worked for him when he started.
My daddy was the first vice in the morning.
What about the cemetery of Bryan?
Is there just one main cemetery, or are they just scattered out?
No, we have two cemeteries right here in the city.
One is operated by the city of Bryan, and the others are operated by no one now.
This one out here was going up until a few years ago.
We started raising sound about it.
Like everything else, we weren't getting what we should have gotten.
So we'll start pitching a fall at the bottom line.
We didn't get one.
They're keeping it now.
That has been .
You mentioned earlier that one of the original cotton gins was right here.
In this same spot.
This is West 18th Street?
Was it 18th Street?
Yes, it was 18th.
Ever since you can remember?
Yes.
What about the other cotton gin in town?
It was right where the food town is now.
That's between Main and Bryan on the first of them.
from the first group.
Can you tell me just a little bit about, do you remember seeing it working?
Oh, yes.
I used to see a wagon of cotton lined up block long.
Yes, I remember those days.
What was the last year that they used cotton?
I couldn't answer that.
Did you ever pick cotton yourself?
No.
I never was fortunate to get out there.
Even though my grandfather, come on.
My grandfather had a, he farmed.
Now this still was incidentally.
That's one of the landmarks on the corner right there, by the way.
It has been there all this time, and that's the past of it, not the present past of it.
The other one passed on.
I'll come back and check with you later.
Let's chill in.

He's been here about seven years, so he couldn't tell you.
History of Brian.
Can you just tell me a little bit of
Like, maybe like a day of what you can remember.
The people at the cotton gin, like what they wore, or...
Same as you today, blue jeans.
Blue jeans?
Really?
See, see, old thing, why did you folks today dress them up?
You called them Levi's.
Yeah.
Of course, it's a ducky front.
Mm-hmm.
Were they like overalls for you?
No.
It was kind of like an apron, you know, with suspenders on it.
What about winning star clothing?
I can't remember just what they wore.
I'm almost sure if they wore anything, they wore more than ladies' nightwear.
now that's about all that i know about really
Well, has there ever been, like, any famous person, like a famous news star or something that's come to this area that really caused a big commotion among the people?
Like, everybody goes down to see the person or something.
Can you think of any?
No.
I can't think of a soul, because back there, if they came, in those days, we couldn't go.
If they could naturally, we wouldn't be interested.
We couldn't go anywhere.
And it's just a little better now.
Do you want to elaborate just a little?
Well, we can go now.
Not because every time we go, they want us to come.
We can't help themselves.
See, there were times you could have the money to buy one of those boats, but you couldn't go in and buy one.
Well, you might have passed that back to them, but like I said, those moose dogs, if they came, we wouldn't have gotten to see them because they weren't welcome on it.
Can you remember that one?
Oh, yes.
Heck, yes.
You remember that, too.
Yeah, that's been that long.
Uh-huh.
It hasn't been that long.
You from where?
What's your name?
Colleen, Texas.
Colleen, Texas.
Well, see, my father's in the Army, and we just traveled all over.
So I've never really stayed in my place.
Well, it's been the same everywhere.
It hasn't been too long since that has changed.
And really, it hasn't changed as much as it should have changed now.
But it's so much better than it was.
But we are, I don't know whether you're going to say accepted.
I don't think that would be the word.
I think I could have thought like I said it then, but now, of course, no one can help themselves.
What about the politics of Brian Manning?
Was there Democrats in him, Republicans?
Well, it's been mostly Democrats as long as I can remember.
That was a Republican house, pardon me.
Was your father a Democrat?
No.
If I'm not mistaken, no man was kind of leaning toward Republicans.
because he's about the only one in the family with that.
Democrats, I think.
I say I think because I have time to go for who he thinks best.
I don't know if he called me a Democrat or not.
One instance of George Wallace going to run.
That's what I mean by where the
There's a big bookstore on the corner.
What's that now on that corner?
Drive-In Bank, isn't it?
There's a big bookstore there.
I remember it quite well, because I remember getting rid of it that one day, and hopped a car, of course.
And something might have came out of the bookstore, so I left off there.
Let me tell you about this.
It's going to make me want to move.
So that's why I remember the ducts were so wet.
I forgot the name of the place.
What about the prejudice in Brian?
Is there a lot of prejudice?
Can you remember ever being a lot?
There's still a lot.
Was it worse back then?
Oh, yes, it was worse.
Oh, yes, definitely.
Certainly.
Can you remember, like you just said, you gave me an example.
Can you remember any other times when it was really...
Yes, we'd go to the store, and you could go in the trolley dresser, you know why, but my boy couldn't do it.
You have to buy it, and it's hoping it's going to fit.
Yeah, that's what I can't understand.
That hasn't been too long, because Neiman Marcus and those big stores, they haven't been too long since they started letting you try them on.
You mean they just wouldn't let you try them on?
Hmm, my color was wrong.
You know, we get it there.
I was working with a lot of them.
Too long, I guess.
That's still going on.
Not that bad now.
They can't discriminate against you now.
But that's why I said she mentioned the OSB because now they can't afford to.
Well, even if we have more, we have a little bit more sense now than we had then.
I'm talking about us black folks.
I said, used to you.
Didn't think I had a nice car.
Mm-mm.
So it is.
It's much better.
Mm-hmm.
And you being over at, uh, Rosenberg, you ought to know a lot about it.
Of course, the smaller the town, the worse it was.
But I'll tell you one thing about it, though.
When we got ready to integrate the school system here, did nobody look back.
Just integrate.
Boom.
Of course, during the time, as late as 71, I can remember that quite well, because we'd been in this thing until I was here working at the time, and they were raising hell about the busing.
I'm like a fool.
I just asked a question.
I said, you mean the bussing is wrong?
Yeah, it's wrong.
I said, well, hell yeah, I was in it all my life.
And it just got wrong.
That's why I say a lot of you folks don't have no sense either.
That was just in 71.
What about your public school that you went to?
Was it an all-black school?
Yes, it was a campfire school.
I think it was a campfire school in 38.
Was it a little country school house, or was it public?
It was a public school right here.
I was there.
E.A.
Kemp High.
We would get the Cleveland, as we do, a lot of it being done now.
We'd get the, in other words, if we want the football uniform, we'd get what Brian Hyde didn't want.
They'd buy them some more.
We'd get that.
Now this, you know, as I talk with y'all, y'all seem to think this is something new to y'all.
Now y'all know better than that.
And you, the Aggies, them sorry stonks used to come up the road to get about 20 a brass.
You got to get out and let them by.
That's the way they do it.
I don't know how long that has been, but that happened.
And back in those days, we may have seen it to get one of these.
Because we ain't got one time to die.

I went to service for a while.
We went over there to fight for you.
Well, let's say with you.

Come back here and they want to kick us some more.
We're getting on and on.
Not anymore.
I think the service helped us because that is the place where we didn't mind.
We don't want to die.
We'd rather live for the country than die for it.
But that's what we did.
We got one time to die.
And we got that instilled in us.
And it's in us today.
Oh, you still find a few of them that draw back.

There's a picture up there.
If you want to see it, you have to go upstairs.
I hadn't been too many years ago.
I couldn't give you the exact date.
I'll say this, though.
There were a lot of the folk in this town that didn't want to do, but they had to follow suit, too, you know.
I know your folk now.
They weren't really afraid.
I believe they weren't.
No, they weren't afraid.
They were scared.
That's a difference.
I think it's different for blacks in a small town than blacks that live in the Army post.
Like, we always lived with blacks, and I never felt... Well, you had a little different culture.
You had a conglomerate culture, like at A&M.
Now, if A&M hadn't been out here when we got ready to integrate, I don't think it would have been as smooth as it was.
And I think A&M was the... Not that they said anything, just being there.
Now you say, well, if it helped that, why didn't it help at Prairie?
Prairie was five miles from Hempstead.
And all they did was let them vote to what's the right now.
They just did that.
So, well, I guess it's because it was a white college.
I guess that meant that Prairie was a black college.
Can you tell me anything about Prairie?
What do you want to know?
Well, like...
Anything you know about it?
Was it a big thing when they first built it?
Oh, I don't know when they first built it, but it was about the biggest state school that I grew up.
See, it's still being run by the .
Of course, you have a few white students.
I know a few white people, of course.
What about, you said you attended Southern?
Oh, Southern University in Baton Rouge, Louisiana.
How was it when you were in college?
Well, it was all black, too.
But I went down there.
to a football game.

And I said to myself, I'm going to school here any time black folk get together and stick together.

Yes, I don't know how, I can tell you when, when, where, and why, because when I, as I remember, there was one there then.

I don't think you're old enough.

I was mad.

I had a lovely time.
But holy cow.
